Bored of sitting at home?¶

This is a tutorial on how to make your own coronavirus map in Python.¶

Stage 0 - idea¶

Create a choropleth map displaing a ratio of coronavirus cases per one milion people for each country.

(choropleth - a map which uses differences in shading, colouring within predefined areas to indicate the average values of a particular quantity in those areas - Google dictionary)

We will need to create a dataset with 2 columns only - cases per milion people and geometry (shape of each country).

It should look like exactly like this:

Stage 1 - data download¶

We have 3 datasets available:

  1. World borders (world_shp)
  2. Population accross the world (population)
  3. Coronavirus data for each country (world_data_df)

We will start with importing necessary libraries and data download.

In [361]:
import geopandas

Stage 2 - Data preprocessing¶

In order to get a desired dataset from Stage 0, we will have to somehow combine this 3 datasets to achieve our goal.

Since in our population column from world shapefile is from 2005 (look up - column pop2005), we will need to get more up-to-date information.

In [362]:
#take 2 columns only 
population = population[['Country_Code', 'Year_2016']]

#join shapefile with population
world_shp_with_population = pandas.merge(world_shp, population,how='left', left_on='iso3', right_on='Country_Code')

#our world shapefile enriched with population ('Year_2016' column)

As we can see, it is enriched with the population column, which has been taken from population dataset (column 'Year_2016'). We name this data world_shp_with_population.

Now, since in our coronavirus data we do not have shape for each country, we will have to use what's available - country centroids (Lat, Long columns). We can easily match country centroids from coronavirus data and polygon geometries from world_shp_with_population to create one table with coronavirus cases for each point, and each point will be matched with country polygon that contains it.

In [363]:
#create geometry with centroids (from lat long columns) for each country it will be useful to join data with world shapefile 
data_point_geometry = geopandas.GeoDataFrame(world_data_df, geometry=geopandas.points_from_xy(world_data_df['Long'],world_data_df['Lat']))
# now our downloaded data is enriched with geometry instead of plain lat, long points - it's needed for further join opearion

# perform join on data, match points with polygons, which are available 
joined_data = geopandas.sjoin(data_point_geometry, world_shp, op='within', how='left')

Currently, we have a dataset with each record per every centroid, mathed with country names (above name column). To not complicate this too much, we will sum coronavirus cases for every country name. Such operation is called grouping.

In [364]:
#sum corona cases for each country
generalised_by_country = joined_data.groupby(['name']).sum()

generalised_by_country.head()

Now we need to add polygon (shape) for each country.

In [365]:
# since columns are named like dates we need to get most recent column name  
today = date.today()
str_date ="{}/{}/{}".format(today.month,today.day-1,str(today.year)[-2:])

#set index of table to name of the country so is could easily join generalised_by_country table
world_shp_with_population = world_shp_with_population.set_index(['name'])

#join (merge) 2 tables and choose only 3 columns
world_shp_with_population_and_cases = pandas.merge(world_shp_with_population, generalised_by_country, \
                                                   how='left', right_index=True, left_index=True)
#get rid of useless columns
world_shp_with_population_and_cases = world_shp_with_population_and_cases[[str_date, 'Year_2016', 'geometry']]

And the last thing that has left is to divide population column with summed coronavirus cases (and multiply by milion obviously)

In [366]:
#divide 
world_shp_with_population_and_cases['cases_per_milion'] = 1000000 * \
    world_shp_with_population_and_cases[str_date] / \
    world_shp_with_population_and_cases['Year_2016']

#get rid of NaN values
world_shp_with_population_and_cases = world_shp_with_population_and_cases.fillna(0)

#get rid of useless columns
world_shp_with_population_and_cases = world_shp_with_population_and_cases[['geometry','cases_per_milion']]

Stage 3 - Plotting¶

At this point we have many options, for example export the data in shp file and import it to MapBox studio or QGIS.

For our purpose it will be the best to just plot the map with matplotlib in choropleth mode, we select data column and scheme (type of division into color classes). There are also other parameters like number of classes and color scheme (cmap).

In [367]:
world_shp_with_population_and_cases.plot(column='cases_per_milion', legend=True, \
                                         scheme='fisherjenks', k=7, cmap='Oranges',\
                                         figsize=(40, 40), edgecolor='grey', linewidth=1);
plt.axis('off');
